      <bioghist encodinganalog="MARC 545">
         <head altrender="biography" id="a2">BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE </head>
         <p>A sexual liberation activist who was instrumental in establishing Lamaze education in
            the U.S. and promoting breastfeeding and who published a NEW YORK TIMES bestseller, "The
            G Spot and Other Discoveries About Human Sexuality," with Beverly Whipple and John D.
            Perry in 1982.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="MARC 520">
         <head id="a3">COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
         <p>Alice Kahn Ladas speeches and articles, correspondence, memos, pamphlets, and clippings.
            Includes a 1943 memo detailing her reasons for wanting an internship with the Fair
            Employment Practices Commission and with a U.S. Congressperson, a 1945 letter of thanks
            from employees of the U.S. Patent Office for her assistance getting their positions
            upgraded, a 1951 letter from Eva Reich of the Wilhelm Reich Foundation, notes about a
            meeting with Eleanor Roosevelt, and a 1991 letter to friends. Pamphlets and clippings
            contain her writing on breast feeding, sexuality and women's liberation, and
            bioenergetic analysis. Included is the program from a speech on “The Sexual Revolution:
            Phase Two” given March 14, 2004 at the New York Society for Ethical Culture, a society
            she has been involved with since childhood.</p>
         <p>Also, an issue of Balanced Living containing an article by Alice Hammarth, "Breast
            Feeding and Bottle Feeding Compared" (October 1960); and an issue of The USA Body
            Psychotherapy Journal containing an article by Alice Kahn Ladas, "An Appreciation of
            Alexander Lowen" (2008).</p>
      </scopecontent>
